Wang et al. [121] reported fluorescent nanocellulose aerogels were synthesised by the combination of carbon dots and titanate nanofibers with TEMPO-oxidised nanocellulose using a Schiff base reaction. The application of fluorescent nanocellulose aerogels for the detection of Cr6+ adsorption was investigated. The determined maximum adsorption capacity of fluorescent nanocellulose aerogels is 543.38 mg/g, achieved under the optimized adsorption parameters. The porous structure of the aerogel, with a specific surface area of 20.53 m²/g and numerous adsorption sites, significantly enhanced its effectiveness. Yuan and colleagues developed a three-dimensional net-like structured fluorescent aerogel using carbon dots [122]. The adsorption experiments aimed to examine the uptake of Cr(VI) on the synthesized fluorescent aerogel. The pseudo-second-order kinetic model and Freundlich model were utilized to clarify the adsorption process, indicating a maximum adsorption capacity for Cr(VI) of 433.5 mg/g. The synthesized aerogel demonstrated a blue fluorescence with a quantum yield of 11.8 % for Cr(VI) sensing, indicating a significant linear relationship between quantum yield and Cr(VI) concentration. Luo et al. utilized a free-radical polymerization technique to create a chitosan-based hydrogel with fluorescent and magnetic characteristics (FMCH) [123]. The synthesized material served as an adsorbent for the removal and identification of Cr (VI) from an aqueous solution. The adsorption isotherms for Cr (VI) conformed to the Freundlich models, indicating a maximum adsorption capacity of 212.1 mg/g at 25 °C. The adsorption kinetics of Cr (VI) onto FMCH conformed to a pseudo-second-order kinetic model. An in-depth examination was conducted to assess the sensitivity of Cr (VI) detection. A negative correlation was observed between Cr (VI) levels and the sustained fluorescence of FMCH-7 when exposed to UV light at a wavelength of 365 nm. The quantum yield of FMCH-7 decreases from 2.3 % to 0 % with varying concentrations of Cr (VI) (Fig. 19
                           ). The quantitative detection of Cr (VI) demonstrated a linear range of 20 to 800 mg/L. The established detection limit for Cr (VI) was determined to be 14.21 mg/L. Table 2
                            illustrates a range of polymer/CD's nanocomposites utilized for metal ion sensing, serving as fluorescent probes and adsorbents.
